nese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes von Mainz-Rieneck was born in 1065 as the daughter of Gerhard von Mainz-Rieneck and Hedwige von Blieskastel. She had at least 1 son with Arnold I GRAAF VAN LOON. She died in 1105, in Borgloon, Limburg, Belgium, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1065–1105":"1065–1105","1060–1135":"1060–1135","1080–1139":"1080–1139","1050–1106":"1050–1106","–Female":"Surnud","1080":"1080","UM 1071":"umbes 1071","1106":"1106","1139":"1139","1105":"1105","1135":"1135","UM 1122":"umbes 1122","1065":"1065","um 1080":"umbes 1080","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","Borgloon, Limburg, Belgium":"Borgloon, Limburg, Belgia","Bayern, Deutschland":"Bayern, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1065–1105":"1065–1105","1060–1135":"1060–1135","1080–1139":"1080–1139","1050–1106":"1050–1106","–Female":"Kuollut","10